General Linear Model

Xiaoying Wang

November 27, 2017

Ordinary Linear Regression

model

  • \(Y\) is \(n*1\) vector,
  • \(X\) is \(n*p\) matrix,
  • \(\beta\) is \(p*1\) vector,
  • \(n\) is the number of observations, \(p\) is the umber of features, \(p<<n\).
  • Assume no multicollinearity exist in \(X_i\), or \(X\) is non-singular matrix, or \(rank(X)=p\)

\[Y=X \beta +\epsilon, \epsilon \sim N(0,\sigma^2) iid\] \[Y\sim N(X\beta ,\sigma^2)\] \[E(Y)=X\beta\]

parameter estimation ordinary least square (OLS)

  • loss function: choose \(\beta\) s.t. \(\sum_{i=1}^{n}(Y_i-\beta_0-X_i\beta_1)^2=(Y-X\beta)^T(Y-X\beta)\) is minimized
  • \(\hat\beta_{OLS}=(X^TX)^{-1}X^TY\)
  • properties of OLS: \(\hat\beta_{OLS}\) is Best Linear Unbiased Estimator (BLUE) of \(\beta\): among all the unbiased estimator of \(\beta\), \(\hat\beta_{OLS}\) has the smallest variance

Ridge Regression deal with multicollinearity

definition of multicollinearity

  • multicollinearity exist if not all \(\lambda_1,...,\lambda_k\) exist s.t. \(\lambda_1+\lambda_2X_{2i}+...+\lambda_kX_{ki}=0\)

effect of multicollinearity

  • since \((X^TX)\) is almost 0, \(\hat\beta_{OLS}=(X^TX)^{-1}X^TY\) is getting larger
  • increase of the variance of \(\hat\beta_{OLS}\),
  • increase in confidence interval

Ridge resression

  • add a \(l_2\) penalty term on the basis of ordinary linear regression, with loss function \[(Y-X\beta)^T(Y-X\beta)+k\beta^2\] \[k>0\] \[min (Y-X\beta)^T(Y-X\beta), s.t. \sum\beta_j^2<C\]

  • \(\hat\beta_{k}=(X^TX+kI)^{-1}X^TY\)

  • as \(k\) increases, \(\hat\beta_{k}\) is more biased, but variance is getting smaller

Least Absolute Shrinkage and Selectionator operator (LASSO)

motivation

  • deal with high dimensional data: \(p>>n\)
  • if \(p>>n\), \((X^TX)^{-1}=0\), we have infinity number of solutions for \(\hat\beta_{OLS}=(X^TX)^{-1}X^TY\). In another word, theres overfitting

LASSO

  • add a \(l_1\) penalty term on the basis of ordinary linear regression, with loss function \[(Y-X\beta)^T(Y-X\beta)+k|\beta|\] \[min (Y-X\beta)^T(Y-X\beta) s.t. \sum|\beta_j|<C\]
  • compare to Ridge regression, LASSO can generate sparsity (eliminate some \(X_i\)): variable selection

Elastic Net

loss function

\[(Y-X\beta)^T(Y-X\beta)+k(\alpha\beta^2+(1-\alpha)|\beta|)\] \[0<\alpha<1\] \[min (Y-X\beta)^T(Y-X\beta) s.t. \sum(\alpha\beta_j^2+(1-\alpha)|\beta_j|)<C\]

  • a compromise between ridge and lasso, or a general case of ridge and lasso
  • lasso: elastic net with \(\alpha=1\)
  • ridge: elastic net with \(\alpha=0\)

Least Angle Regression

  • a variable selection algorithm compromising Forward stepwise regression and forward stagewiseregression

the basic steps of the Least-angle regression algorithm are:

  • Start with all coefficients \(\beta _{j}\) equal to zero.
  • Find the predictor \(x_{j}\) most correlated with \(y\)
  • Increase the coefficient \(\beta _{j}\) in the direction of the sign of its correlation with \(y\). Take residuals \(r=y-\hat {y}\) along the way. Stop when some other predictor \(x_{k}\) has as much correlation with \(r\) as \(x_{j}\) has.
  • Increase \((\beta _{j},\beta _{k})\) in their joint least squares direction, until some other predictor \(x_{m}\) has as much correlation with the residual \(r\).
  • Continue until: all predictors are in the model

When \(Y\) are count, categorical variables

Different of GLM from linear regression

  • Response variable \(Y\)
    • Linear regression: Y follows normal distribution
    • GLM: \(Y\) can have arbitrary distributions: binomial, multinomial, possion
  • Link funtion g(Y)
    • Linear regression: \(g(Y)=Y\), the response Y itself varies linearly with predicted values \(X\)
    • GLM: a function of \(Y\) varies linearly with predicted values \(X\), eg: \(g(Y)=logit(Y)\) for logistic regression

Components of GLM

  • Distribution of \(Y\): probability distribution from exponential family
    • exponential family: a family of pdf(pmf) is called exponention if \[f(x|\mathbf{\theta})=h(x)c(\mathbf{\theta})e^{\sum_{i=1}^{k}w_i(\mathbf{\theta})t_i(x)}\]
    • eg.Bernoulli, Binomial,multinomial, Normal, poisson
  • Link funtion \(g(Y)\)
    • \(g(Y)=w(Y)\): canonical link
      • \(Y\sim Normal(\mu,\sigma^2)\) assume \(\sigma\) is known, then \(g(Y)=Y\): identical link
      • \(Y\sim Bernoulli(p)\) then \(g(Y)=log(\frac{Y}{1-Y})\): logit link (logistic regression)
      • \(Y\sim Poission(\lambda)\) then \(g(Y)=log(Y)\): log link
  • Linear system
    • \(g(Y)=X\beta\)

Examples

For all examples:

  • true model is \(y=X\beta+\epsilon\)
  • where \(\epsilon\sim N(0,I)\)

ex1.

Small signal. Lots of noise.

  • \(\beta=(1,1,0,...,0)^T\), 2s 1, and 498s 0
  • \(p=500>n=100\)
  • Uncorrelated predictors: \[X_i\sim N(0,I), iid\]
library(MASS)  # Package needed to generate correlated precictors
## Warning: package 'MASS' was built under R version 3.2.5
library(glmnet)  # Package to fit ridge/lasso/elastic net models
## Warning: package 'glmnet' was built under R version 3.2.5
## Loading required package: Matrix
## Loading required package: foreach
## Warning: package 'foreach' was built under R version 3.2.5
## Loaded glmnet 2.0-5
# Generate data
set.seed(19875)  # Set seed for reproducibility
n <- 100  # Number of observations
p <- 500  # Number of predictors included in model
real_p <- 2  # Number of true predictors
x <- matrix(rnorm(n*p), nrow=n, ncol=p)
y <- apply(x[,1:real_p], 1, sum) + rnorm(n)

# Split data into train (2/3) and test (1/3) sets
train_rows <- sample(1:n, .66*n)
x.train <- x[train_rows, ]
x.test <- x[-train_rows, ]

y.train <- y[train_rows]
y.test <- y[-train_rows]
# Fit models 
# (For plots on left):
fit.lasso <- glmnet(x.train, y.train, family="gaussian", alpha=1)
fit.ridge <- glmnet(x.train, y.train, family="gaussian", alpha=0)
fit.elnet <- glmnet(x.train, y.train, family="gaussian", alpha=.5)


# 10-fold Cross validation for each alpha = 0, 0.1, ... , 0.9, 1.0
# (For plots on Right)
for (i in 0:10) {
    assign(paste("fit", i, sep=""), cv.glmnet(x.train, y.train, type.measure="mse", 
                                              alpha=i/10,family="gaussian"))
}
# Plot solution paths:
par(mfrow=c(3,2))
# For plotting options, type '?plot.glmnet' in R console
plot(fit.lasso, xvar="lambda")
plot(fit10, main="LASSO")

plot(fit.ridge, xvar="lambda")
plot(fit0, main="Ridge")

plot(fit.elnet, xvar="lambda")
plot(fit5, main="Elastic Net")

yhat0 <- predict(fit0, s=fit0$lambda.1se, newx=x.test)
yhat1 <- predict(fit1, s=fit1$lambda.1se, newx=x.test)
yhat2 <- predict(fit2, s=fit2$lambda.1se, newx=x.test)
yhat3 <- predict(fit3, s=fit3$lambda.1se, newx=x.test)
yhat4 <- predict(fit4, s=fit4$lambda.1se, newx=x.test)
yhat5 <- predict(fit5, s=fit5$lambda.1se, newx=x.test)
yhat6 <- predict(fit6, s=fit6$lambda.1se, newx=x.test)
yhat7 <- predict(fit7, s=fit7$lambda.1se, newx=x.test)
yhat8 <- predict(fit8, s=fit8$lambda.1se, newx=x.test)
yhat9 <- predict(fit9, s=fit9$lambda.1se, newx=x.test)
yhat10 <- predict(fit10, s=fit10$lambda.1se, newx=x.test)

mse0 <- mean((y.test - yhat0)^2)
mse1 <- mean((y.test - yhat1)^2)
mse2 <- mean((y.test - yhat2)^2)
mse3 <- mean((y.test - yhat3)^2)
mse4 <- mean((y.test - yhat4)^2)
mse5 <- mean((y.test - yhat5)^2)
mse6 <- mean((y.test - yhat6)^2)
mse7 <- mean((y.test - yhat7)^2)
mse8 <- mean((y.test - yhat8)^2)
mse9 <- mean((y.test - yhat9)^2)
mse10 <- mean((y.test - yhat10)^2)

mse=c(mse0,mse1,mse2,mse3,mse4,mse5,mse6,mse7,mse8,mse9,mse10)

for(i in 1:length(mse)){
  print(paste('alpha=',(i-1)/10,' ',mse[i]))
  }
## [1] "alpha= 0   3.56628706537719"
## [1] "alpha= 0.1   3.19596891232558"
## [1] "alpha= 0.2   2.61216305188221"
## [1] "alpha= 0.3   2.23924225313516"
## [1] "alpha= 0.4   2.20375451901338"
## [1] "alpha= 0.5   1.82620374830924"
## [1] "alpha= 0.6   1.91529154172499"
## [1] "alpha= 0.7   1.77983042625268"
## [1] "alpha= 0.8   1.66702662891965"
## [1] "alpha= 0.9   1.62176040215838"
## [1] "alpha= 1   1.69199096356385"

ex2

  • Varying signals. High correlation between predictors
  • \(\beta=(10,10,5,5,1,...,1,0,...,0)\), 10s 1, 36s 0
  • \(p=50,n=100\)
  • Correlated predictors: \(Cov(X)_{ij}=(0.7)^{|i-j|}\)
set.seed(19873)
n <- 100    # Number of observations
p <- 50     # Number of predictors included in model
CovMatrix <- outer(1:p, 1:p, function(x,y) {.7^abs(x-y)})
x <- mvrnorm(n, rep(0,p), CovMatrix)
y <- 10 * apply(x[, 1:2], 1, sum) + 
  5 * apply(x[, 3:4], 1, sum) +
  apply(x[, 5:14], 1, sum) +
  rnorm(n)

# Split data into train and test sets
train_rows <- sample(1:n, .66*n)
x.train <- x[train_rows, ]
x.test <- x[-train_rows, ]

y.train <- y[train_rows]
y.test <- y[-train_rows]
fit.lasso <- glmnet(x.train, y.train, family="gaussian", alpha=1)
fit.ridge <- glmnet(x.train, y.train, family="gaussian", alpha=0)
fit.elnet <- glmnet(x.train, y.train, family="gaussian", alpha=.5)


# 10-fold Cross validation for each alpha = 0, 0.1, ... , 0.9, 1.0
fit.lasso.cv <- cv.glmnet(x.train, y.train, type.measure="mse", alpha=1, 
                          family="gaussian")
fit.ridge.cv <- cv.glmnet(x.train, y.train, type.measure="mse", alpha=0,
                          family="gaussian")
fit.elnet.cv <- cv.glmnet(x.train, y.train, type.measure="mse", alpha=.5,
                          family="gaussian")

for (i in 0:10) {
    assign(paste("fit", i, sep=""), cv.glmnet(x.train, y.train, type.measure="mse", 
                                              alpha=i/10,family="gaussian"))
}
# Plot solution paths:
par(mfrow=c(3,2))
# For plotting options, type '?plot.glmnet' in R console
plot(fit.lasso, xvar="lambda")
plot(fit10, main="LASSO")

plot(fit.ridge, xvar="lambda")
plot(fit0, main="Ridge")

plot(fit.elnet, xvar="lambda")
plot(fit5, main="Elastic Net")

yhat6 <- predict(fit6, s=fit6$lambda.1se, newx=x.test)
yhat7 <- predict(fit7, s=fit7$lambda.1se, newx=x.test)
yhat8 <- predict(fit8, s=fit8$lambda.1se, newx=x.test)
yhat9 <- predict(fit9, s=fit9$lambda.1se, newx=x.test)
yhat10 <- predict(fit10, s=fit10$lambda.1se, newx=x.test)

mse0 <- mean((y.test - yhat0)^2)
mse1 <- mean((y.test - yhat1)^2)
mse2 <- mean((y.test - yhat2)^2)
mse3 <- mean((y.test - yhat3)^2)
mse4 <- mean((y.test - yhat4)^2)
mse5 <- mean((y.test - yhat5)^2)
mse6 <- mean((y.test - yhat6)^2)
mse7 <- mean((y.test - yhat7)^2)
mse8 <- mean((y.test - yhat8)^2)
mse9 <- mean((y.test - yhat9)^2)
